===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
In oracle bone inscriptions, {{Han compound|ls=ic|䇂|見|t1=chisel|t2=kneeling person with a huge eye|nocap=y}}. It depicts a person getting their eye ([[目]]) gouged out, a common punishment for slaves in ancient China. Compare {{zh-l|*民}}, {{zh-l|*臧}}. 

In bronze inscriptions, the phonetic component {{och-l|東}} was added, making the character {{liushu|psc|adj=yse|nocap=yes}}. 

In the modern form {{zh-l|*䇂}} has corrupted into {{zh-l|*立}}. The bottom {{zh-l|*里}} derives from {{zh-l|*東}} combining with {{zh-l|*土}}, similar to {{zh-l|*重}}.

===Etymology===
; “child; servant boy; virgin; bare”
: {{zh-ref|Löffler (1966)}} compares it to {{cog|tbq-kuk}} {{m|und|dong||boy}}; see also {{w|Rengmitca}} {{m|und||'''tong'''-kléng'|boy}}, Areng {{m|und||'''thon'''-dén|boy}} ({{zh-ref|Löffler, 1960}}). <!-- Schuessler calls it "Khami", but Löffler did not specific this. --> {{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}} also compares it to {{cog|hmx}}: {{cog|mww|tub||son}}, {{cog|ium|dorn||son}}.
; “shaman”
: {{zh-ref|Norman and Mei (1976)}} proposed that the Min Chinese word for “shaman” (*''-dəŋ<sup>A</sup>''), written as {{lang|zh|童}}, is from an Austroasiatic substratum, cognate with {{cog|vi|đồng}}, {{cog|mnw|ဒံၚ်|tr=tòŋ||to dance while under daemonic possession; to proceed by leaps}}, {{m|mnw|ဒေါၚ်|tr=tòŋ||shaman called in to organise ''kəlok'' dances}}. This is rebutted in {{zh-ref|Sagart (2008)}}, who cited the wide distribution of the sense “magician; sorcerer” in late 19th-century & early 20th-century Chinese and the secondary meaning of {{lang|zh|童}} as “servant; messenger”, describing the resemblance between the Min and Austroasiatic terms as “undoubtedly fortuitous”.

